metaData.descriptionCS: The examinee responds orally to items that require the application of mathematical principles to real life situations.

questions.title: Item 1. 2
questions.topInstructionsHTML: How many ears do you have?

questions.title: Item 2. smallest
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Here are some seals at the zoo. Touch the smallest seal.

questions.title: Item 3. circle
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Touch the circle.

questions.title: Item 4. 1–2–3–4
questions.topInstructionsHTML:
These children are going to the zoo. Point to them (point to each child) and count them aloud as you point.

The examinee must say “1-2-3‑4” with no omissions, repeats, or additions, and point to a different child for each spoken number.

questions.title: Item 5. 4
questions.topInstructionsHTML: How many children are there?

questions.title: Item 6. tallest
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Touch the tallest giraffe.

questions.title: Item 7. 3 fish
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Touch the picture that shows only three fish.

questions.title: Item 8. 3
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Touch the number three.

questions.title: Item 9. 5
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Touch the number five.

questions.title: Item 10. 2 apples
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Touch the picture that shows this many (point to the 2) apples.

questions.title: Item 11. 8
questions.topInstructionsHTML:
How many seals are there?

(The examinee is not required to count aloud.)

questions.title: Item 12. shows 5
questions.topInstructionsHTML:
Show me five seals. Touch them with your fingers.

(The examinee may touch the 5 seals individually or all at once, or may cover all of the seals except 5.)

questions.title: Item 13. 7
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Point to the 7. Say, What number is this?

questions.title: Item 14. 6
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Jessie has two peanuts (point to the top row) for the elephants, and Paco has four peanuts (point to the bottom row). How many peanuts do they have altogether?

questions.title: Item 15. triangle
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Which one here (point to the bottom row) goes here (point to the space above the line)?

questions.title: Item 16. seals
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Are there more people or more seals?

questions.title: Item 17. 6
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Point to the blank. Say, What number is missing?

questions.title: Item 18. 12
questions.topInstructionsHTML:
Point to the 12. Say, What number is this?

If the examinee says one–two, say, Tell me another way to say the number.

questions.title: Item 19. 17
questions.topInstructionsHTML:
Point to the 17. Say, What number is this?

If the examinee says one–seven, say, Tell me another way to say the number.

questions.title: Item 20. third
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Point to the first person in line. Say, This person is first in line. Touch the person who is third in line.

questions.title: Item 21. 4
questions.topInstructionsHTML: There are nine people in line. If five people leave the line, how many will be left?

questions.title: Item 22. +
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Touch the one that means add or plus.

questions.title: Item 23. 5
questions.topInstructionsHTML:
The children are counting how many animals they saw. This graph shows that they saw (point to each row as you name it) elephants, giraffes, ducks, seals, and tigers. These numbers (point) show how many of each animal they saw.

Point to the seal. Say, How many seals did they see?

questions.title: Item 24. ducks
questions.topInstructionsHTML:
Which animal did they see the least?

(The examinee may also point to the duck.)

questions.title: Item 25. 6
questions.topInstructionsHTML: If four more ducks came to swim, how many ducks would there be altogether?

questions.title: Item 26. 28
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Point to the 29. Say, When counting, what number comes just before this one?

questions.title: Item 27. 2, 5
questions.topInstructionsHTML:
Complete this number sentence (point) to tell how many monkeys there are altogether.

Point to the first blank. Say, What number should go here?

Point to the second blank. Say, What number should go here?

(For credit, both questions must be answered correctly.)

questions.title: Item 28. 38, 45, 51, 67
questions.topInstructionsHTML:
Harry has to hang up the football shirts in number order: first the lowest number, then the next lowest, and so on. (For credit, all four parts of this question must be answered correctly.)
a) Touch the shirt he will hang up first.
b) Touch the shirt he will hang up next.  
c) Touch the shirt he will hang up next.  
d) Touch the shirt he will hang up last.

questions.title: Item 29. 235
questions.topInstructionsHTML:
Point to 235. Say, What number is this?

If the examinee says two-three-five or two-thirty-five say, Tell me another way to say the number.

questions.title: Item 30. Friday
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Carmen’s birthday is November twenty-sixth. On what day of the week is her birthday?

questions.title: Item 31. pounds
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Here are three units for measuring weight (point to each as you read): tons, ounces, and pounds. Which of these works best to measure the weight of a man?

questions.title: Item 32. 25
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Each dot on this line should have a number. Touch the dot that stands for twenty-five.

questions.title: Item 33. 50
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Point to dot A. Say, What number should go here?

questions.title: Item 34. one o’clock
questions.topInstructionsHTML: What time does this clock show?

questions.title: Item 35. 8:30
questions.topInstructionsHTML: What time does this clock show?

questions.title: Item 36. 60 cents
questions.topInstructionsHTML:
Be sure the examinee has access to paper and a pencil. Say, You may use this paper and pencil to work the rest of the problems.

This man is selling candy. Here is his sign (point). At thirty cents for a piece of candy, how much will two pieces cost?

questions.title: Item 37. 32
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Point to the blank. Say, What number comes next?

questions.title: Item 38. minutes
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Here are three units for measuring time (point to each as you read): seconds, minutes, and hours. Which of these works best to measure how long it takes most people to eat breakfast?

questions.title: Item 39. 5
questions.topInstructionsHTML:
If starting with this item, be sure the examinee has access to paper and a pencil. Say, You may use this paper and pencil to work the problems.

Here are seven elephants. Some more elephants join them, so there are twelve altogether. How many elephants joined them?

questions.title: Item 40. 18
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Michael delivers groceries for the local supermarket. One day he delivered five bags to Mrs. Brown, nine bags to Mr. Gomez, and four bags to Mr. Tran. How many bags did he deliver that day?

questions.title: Item 41. 700
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Juana counted all the boxes of pencils in the supply room. There were seven full boxes. If each box holds one hundred pencils, how many pencils were there altogether?

questions.title: Item 42. 4
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Three children wanted to pet the rabbits. They divided all the rabbits equally among themselves. How many rabbits did each child get to pet?

questions.title: Item 43. 65 cents in coins
questions.topInstructionsHTML:
Here are some coins. If you need exactly sixty-five cents, which of these coins would you use?

(The examinee may point to the coins or name them.)

questions.title: Item 44. 85 cents
questions.topInstructionsHTML: How much are these coins worth altogether?

questions.title: Item 45. 12
questions.topInstructionsHTML: How many paper clips will it take altogether to go all the way around the envelope?

questions.title: Item 46. shows 4
questions.topInstructionsHTML:
Show me one-half of all the sheep. Touch them with your fingers.

(The examinee may touch the 4 sheep individually or all at once, cover all the sheep except 4, or show a line to divide the group in half.)

questions.title: Item 47. 100 pounds
questions.topInstructionsHTML: This elephant (point) weighs 650 pounds, and this one (point) weighs 550 pounds. How many more pounds does the bigger one weigh than the smaller one?

questions.title: Item 48. 10
questions.topInstructionsHTML: The zoo has two times as many lions as goats. The zoo has five goats. How many lions does the zoo have?

questions.title: Item 49. 60 cents
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Miguel bought two tickets for twenty cents each. How much change did he get from a dollar?

questions.title: Item 50. method
questions.topInstructionsHTML:
Use your paper and pencil to show me what you did to get the answer.

If the examinee shows only one valid step, say, Show the two steps you did to get the answer.

If the examinee gave an incorrect response on Item 49 and then obtains the correct answer on Item 50, do not change the score for Item 49.

scoreButtons.label:
Accept any valid method that includes 
two steps and produces the correct answer. 
No oral response is necessary.

Examples:

Total cost is forty cents
$0.20 + $0.20 = $0.40, or  

$0.20 x 2 = $0.40, and
$1.00 – $0.40 = $0.60

Subtract twenty cents twice
$1.00 – $0.20 = $0.80, and
$0.80 – $0.20 = $0.60

questions.title: Item 51. 3 hrs 15 min
questions.topInstructionsHTML:
The Silver Streak (point to name) leaves New York at 8:00 AM and arrives in Baltimore the same day at the time shown on the chart. How much time does the trip take?

You may read aloud any word requested by the examinee.

questions.title: Item 52. equation
questions.topInstructionsHTML:
Use your paper and pencil to show me how to check this problem using addition.

If the examinee sets up the problem correctly but omits the answer,

      or

point to the space where the answer belongs and say, What number goes here?

(If the examinee sets up the problem correctly but makes an addition error and arrives at an incorrect answer, give credit.)

questions.title: Item 53. 3/4
questions.topInstructionsHTML: What fraction of this shape is shaded?

questions.title: Item 54. 2
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Which digit is in the hundred-thousands place?

questions.title: Item 55. 20
questions.topInstructionsHTML: There were eighty people at a seal show. They all fit into four rows of seats. If an equal number of people sat in each row, how many were in each row?

questions.title: Item 56. 3/5
questions.topInstructionsHTML: A family has completed two-fifths of a trip. What fraction of the trip remains?

questions.title: Item 57. 9,070
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Round this number to the nearest ten.

questions.title: Item 58. 3/13
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Here are thirteen shapes. If Jason closes his eyes and picks one, what is the probability that he will choose a circle?

questions.title: Item 59. 3/4
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Which of these fractions is the largest in value?

questions.title: Item 60. 17 ones
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Thirty-seven equals two tens and how many ones?

questions.title: Item 61. 45 min
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Here is a sign for the seal shows. If the show starting at 2:00 PM ends at 2:45 PM, how much time is there before the beginning of the next show?

questions.title: Item 62. 3 inches
questions.topInstructionsHTML: How many inches long is this pencil?

questions.title: Item 63. 8 degrees
questions.topInstructionsHTML: This graph shows the high temperatures for the first ten days of August. What was the difference in temperature between the hottest day and the coolest day?

questions.title: Item 64. 6 feet
questions.topInstructionsHTML: How many feet are in two yards?

questions.title: Item 65. 9
questions.topInstructionsHTML: There are sixty-seven children in the fourth grade at Applewood School. If only eight children can sit around a lunchroom table, how many tables will be needed when the fourth grade goes to lunch?

questions.title: Item 66. 60 degrees
questions.topInstructionsHTML: How many degrees are in the angle marked with the x?

questions.title: Item 67. 8
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Shawna got these four grades on math quizzes that she took this week (point to the scores). What was her average math quiz grade?

questions.title: Item 68. 0.47
questions.topInstructionsHTML:
This grid has one hundred boxes, with ten boxes in each row. What is the decimal that represents how much of the grid is shaded?

If the examinee says a fraction instead of a decimal (e.g., 47 over 100 or 47 out of 100), say, What is that as a decimal?

scoreButtons.label:
point four seven (.47)
or
point forty-seven
or
forty-seven hundredths

questions.title: Item 69. equation
questions.topInstructionsHTML:
Use your paper and pencil to show me how to check this problem using division. 

If the examinee sets up the problem correctly but omits the answer,

2544 ÷ 53 =
        or
2544 ÷ 48 =

point to the space where the answer belongs and say, What number goes here?

(If the examinee sets up the problem correctly but makes a division error and arrives at an incorrect answer, give credit.)

questions.title: Item 70. 2.615
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Round this number to the nearest thousandth.

questions.title: Item 71. 3
questions.topInstructionsHTML: Rectangle ABCD is shown here. What is the length of side CD (point)?

questions.title: Item 72. 2, –1
questions.topInstructionsHTML:
What are the coordinates of point A (point)?

(For credit, the examinee must give the numbers in this sequence.)

questions.title: Item 73. 7 and 11
questions.topInstructionsHTML:
Which of these numbers are prime numbers?

If the examinee gives only one, say, Are there any more?

(For credit, the examinee must give both numbers in any order and no incorrect numbers.)

questions.title: Item 74. 0.6
questions.topInstructionsHTML:
What is the decimal equivalent of three-fifths?

If the examinee says a fraction instead of a decimal (e.g., 6 over 10), say, What is that as a decimal?

questions.title: Item 75. 10 sq cm
questions.topInstructionsHTML: The volume of this rectangular prism is seventy cubic centimeters. What is the area of the shaded side?

questions.title: Item 76. 0.41

questions.title: Item 77. 6
questions.topInstructionsHTML: How many people can share four bags of popcorn if each person gets two-thirds of a bag?

questions.title: Item 78. 20%
questions.topInstructionsHTML:
The Smallville Tigers baseball team played eighty games last year. They won sixteen of them. What percentage of their games did they win?

If the examinee says point twenty or one-fifth, say, What is that as a percentage?

questions.title: Item 79. 10 feet
questions.topInstructionsHTML: What is the value of y?

questions.title: Item 80. 2
questions.topInstructionsHTML: What is the slope of the line that connects the points six, thirteen and one, three?

questions.title: Item 81. 6π
questions.topInstructionsHTML: What is the circumference of this circle, in terms of pi?

questions.title: Item 82. 2x + 6 = 16
questions.topInstructionsHTML:
Use your paper and pencil to write an equation that would allow you to solve the following problem:

Armand is taking orders for two kinds of pizza. There are six more orders for pepperoni pizzas than there are for cheese pizzas. If sixteen pizzas are ordered altogether, how many cheese pizzas are ordered?

Let x represent the number of cheese pizzas ordered.

If the examinee gives a numerical answer instead of an equation, say, Now write an equation to solve the problem.

questions.topInstructionsHTML: What is the distance between the points seven, four and ten, one?

observations.label: Made errors on problems involving visual-spatial elements (shapes, graphs/charts, math symbols: =, +, >)
Performed calculations mentally (not on paper) and derived the wrong answer
Responded to a different question than the one that was asked
Developed an incorrect equation for a word problem
